1125 To be expended for the Bullying Prevention Project in accordance with Title 16, Chapter 28B,
1126 Code of Alabama 1975. The State Superintendent of Education shall distribute the above
1127 appropriation as grants to local education agencies. These agencies may be awarded funds only
1128 after application to the State Department of Education. The grant application process may
1129 require the submission of plans by the applicant to meet the requirements set forth in Chapter
1130 28B of Title 16. In the awarding of grants, preference will be given to applicants seeking to
1131 develop and implement evidence-based practices to promote a school environment that is free of
1132 harassment, intimidation, violence, and threats of violence. This program may also address tier
1133 one and tier two of the school-based mental health model of all students receiving prevention
1134 education and peers working to support and identify at-risk students. Additionally, the program
1135 may focus to increase school safety through early identification of at-risk students,
1136 minimizing disciplinary infractions including school suspensions and expulsions. The program
1137 may provide grade level prevention curriculum for all students and, in that case, the
1138 curriculum must be updated annually to remain current and relevant to current trends that youth
1139 face in their lives. Any applicable prevention curriculum must be comprehensive and satisfy the
1140 following state mandates: Erin's Law, Jamari Terrell Williams Student Bullying Prevention Act,
1141 Jason Flatt Act, Price Hornsby Act, and Drugs and Alcohol. In addition, any program related to
1142 mental health should be flexible enough to focus on the greatest mental health needs for each
1143 individual school. For accountability purposes, reporting data must include the number of
1144 students engaged in the programs, the number of students supported, and the number of students
1145 referred to adults as at-risk.
