1175 This appropriation shall be used for the State Department of Education, in consultation with
1176 the Department of Early Childhood Education, to fund a program to be known as the Governor's
1177 Turnaround Schools. These grants are for the lowest performing public elementary schools which
1178 are identified as underperforming by the State Superintendent in consideration of the
1179 provisions of the Alabama Accountability Act, the State Report Card System, and other criteria
1180 as determined by the State Superintendent. The intent of these grants is to identify and target
1181 specific deficiencies of each individual underperforming elementary school and target said
1182 deficiencies with high quality and innovative educational supports. In consultation with these
1183 schools as well as the local education agencies that respectively oversee these schools, the
1184 State Department of Education will develop and oversee a comprehensive plan for school
1185 improvement. It is the intention of this provision that all areas of the State Department,
1186 including Alabama Reading Initiative, Alabama Math, Science, and Technology Initiative, Office
1187 of Mathematics Improvement, and Office of School Improvement, will work together to best serve
1188 these selected schools. Schools previously named to this list will be known as Cohort 1.
1189 Beginning with the fiscal year 2027 Budget Request, the State Department will recommend a
1190 pathway for schools in Cohort 1 to exit this program, and the Department will recommend new
1191 schools to replace those exiting the program in subsequent years. These schools may be known as
1192 Cohort 2 and so forth. The State Superintendent may also request additional funds so that
1193 additional cohorts can be expanded as Cohort 1 schools leave the program over the next few
1194 years. Any expansion of new Cohorts should be modest with respect to the purpose of this
1195 program which is expected to offer extraordinary supports to a relatively limited number of
1196 schools at a time. The State Department of Education should annually produce written progress
1197 reports on these schools to the Chair of the House Ways and Means - Education Committee, the
