1819 To be distributed as grants to monuments to commemorate historical events and places,
1820 historical skills centers, cultural heritage parks, historic sites, commissions, boards,
1821 agencies, and authorities that are not owned, operated, or otherwise under the control of the
1822 Alabama Historical Commission or other state agencies. Grants will be awarded to entities that
1823 reflect a historical education-based mission and concentrate on historical educational
1824 programming. Preference shall be given to: (1) any property constructed prior to 1840 that is
1825 listed in or eligible for the National Register of Historic Places and that are publicly owned
1826 and accessible to the public; or (2) any property in Alabama built in 1943 or before, and is
1827 listed in or eligible for the National Register of Historic Places or any property built after
1828 1943 that significantly contributed to the civil rights movement. Grant amounts shall not
1829 exceed $100,000 for any one entity and must be used within two years of receiving, with the
1830 first three grants reserved for Old State Bank for $100,000, Somerville Courthouse for $75,000,
1831 and Princess Theater for $85,000. Grants will not be awarded to any entity receiving funding
1832 directly or indirectly from the Education Trust Fund or the General Fund nor may grants be
1833 awarded to any private or for-profit business or organization.
